{"id":"d=origam-topic-4404//p=867955409c6847508007402a37912d4e","tags":{"__document_id":["origam-topic-4404"],"__file_type":["text/plain"],"__file_id":["8fadd9b162b14088bf2bc2ed9f13c06e"],"__file_part":["2a7502c93e824b7dbb73d748270ffba6"],"__part_n":["3"],"__sect_n":["0"],"source":["origam-community"],"topicId":["4404"],"categoryId":["61"],"url":["https://community.origam.com/t/how-to-adjust-ux-ui-of-the-client-application/4404"],"title":["How to adjust UX/UI of the client application"],"imagesFound":["11"],"imagesDescribed":["11"],"imageUrl":["https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/a/a388424a98f0d8b427f4923d6521d3f2a645bdd5.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/e/ed5dca9cd0482563fce3dabab006bff3e46ec28e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/b/b1b8d45cb8dff3797401bff08eb677f59c059a67.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/083f1cf3377ad4441cc8bdf267b814e121f275ee.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/4b6cbd4641981a6580362124f2208a5e042f2a3e.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/f/ffc5c8703e2f6dd56a18661ee9098cdbb64c11f7.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/7/757f508ecacc20fc28a5bb41fbcb2bd2cb09e9d0.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/4/40d3044d81054f4189021fce51d605019fa13edf.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/0bc90246bb802c4f770ac7426df4e34c010ea9c5.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/57b4ebb877107c4565dc52e95058ec6daebfef62.png","https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/8/8a565e0e2c67e7348fc83de8b7795515a49bf01a.png"]},"payload":{"url":"","schema":"20231218A","file":"content.txt","text":" \u0022References\u0022 section lists \u0022ConfirmationMessage,\u0022 \u0022ConfirmationRule,\u0022 and a reference to \u0022Workflow\u0022 named \u0022MyWorkflow.\u0022 The overall purpose is to define the specifications and behaviors of a custom action in a workflow environment.\n\n\n  \n The following settings are also important here: \n \n  ActionType : Here are different options for what your action button can do \u2014 for example, open a form or run a workflow in the background. \n  IsModalDialog : Instead of a form will use modal dialog window. \n  Mode : Specifies relation between the action and data. \n  Placement : Where the button will be placed in the screen \u2013 toolbar or panel, see above. \n  RefreshAfterReturn : You can setup here, that after the end the screen will refresh. This can be useful, for example, when you add a new record in the workflow. If you set the  RefreshCompleteForm  value here, the entire screen will reload after the workflow runs, and you\u2019ll see your record among the existing data without having to manually refresh the page. \n  SaveAfterWorkflow : This is used in scenarios where a workflow action returns data to the form from which the action was initiated \u2013 it saves then the edited form. It performs the same function as when a user clicks the Save button. \n  Rule : Rule that determines when the button is displayed and when it is not, see  here . \n \n More on action settings is  here . \n   Screen Condition \n Now that the action for the entity is ready, all that\u2019s left is to \u201Cactivate\u201D it for a specific screen. \n To do this, you need to create a new  Screen Condition  for your UI action and select the target screen where your action button will appear. \n The model element might look like this, for example: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/0/0bc90246bb802c4f770ac7426df4e34c010ea9c5.png]\nDescription: The image depicts a software interface sidebar focused on task management. The main section labeled \u0022Task\u0022 contains expandable items: \u0022_Ancestors,\u0022 \u0022Fields,\u0022 \u0022Filters,\u0022 and \u0022UI Actions.\u0022 Under \u0022UI Actions,\u0022 a specific task is highlighted as \u0022NewTaskForMe,\u0022 which appears to have sub-items, including \u0022Screen Condition\u0022 and another entry labeled \u0022Task.\u0022 The layout suggests a hierarchical structure for organizing tasks within a software environment, likely intended for project management or workflow coordination.\n\n\n  \n   Parameter Mapping \n In some cases, you may need your action button to pass a parameter to the workflow, such as the Id of the record for which this action was triggered. \n You can create a parameter using the  Parameter Mapping  function on your UI action element, and it might look something like this: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/5/57b4ebb877107c4565dc52e95058ec6daebfef62.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface for configuring parameter mapping, specifically focused on the item labeled \u0022IN_TaskId.\u0022 The interface includes sections labeled (Info) and (Schema Item), showing details such as \u0022Ancestors\u0022 set to False and \u0022Inheritable\u0022 also set to False. The field \u0022Name\u0022 is highlighted with the value \u0022IN_TaskId.\u0022 In the section labeled Misc, two additional fields are presented: \u0022Field\u0022 with the value \u0022Id\u0022 and \u0022Type\u0022 listed as \u0022Current.\u0022 The apparent purpose of this interface is to define and manage parameter mapping for data schemas in a software application.\n\n\n  \n Notes: \nIn the \u0060Field\u0060 property, you can enter the name of the specific field you want to pass in the parameter (in this case, \u0060Id\u0060). You can also enter a period (\u201C.\u201D), which passes the entire row to the parameter, or a slash (\u201C/\u201D), which passes the entire row and all its child records. \n The UI action with a parameter looks like this, for example: \n  \n\n\n[Image: https://community.origam.com/uploads/default/original/2X/8/8a565e0e2c67e7348fc83de8b7795515a49bf01a.png]\nDescription: The image displays a user interface component, likely from a software application, showcasing a hierarchical tree structure related to task management. At the top level, the category is labeled \u0022UI Actions,\u0022 with a sub-item \u0022CloseCurrentTask.\u0022 Below that, a section titled \u0022Parameter Mappings\u0022 is highlighted, containing an item named \u0022IN_TaskId.\u0022 Additional items include \u0022Screen Condition\u0022 and \u0022Task,\u0022 suggesting a framework for managing parameters and conditions related to tasks within the application context. The layout implies an organized approach to handling user interface actions and task-related parameters.\n\n\n","vector_provider":"AI.Ollama.OllamaTextEmbeddingGenerator","vector_generator":"__","last_update":"2026-05-01T23:57:59"},"vector":[0.0013297368,-0.01380064,-0.08040565,0.021720454,-0.00017077706,-0.036955673,0.03039467,0.019908408,-0.023527028,0.0035717073,-0.007073561,-0.023793148,0.016715394,0.02704481,0.030779086,0.0137387235,0.014708164,0.023665238,0.05121463,0.011136163,-0.008790447,-0.0035314618,0.046864927,0.025998404,-0.00877578,0.056247592,0.0058973012,-0.042205,-0.010340575,0.007843291,0.03309877,-0.020704107,-0.032864366,-0.008364633,0.0016151349,-0.011837298,-0.037792552,-0.011185446,-0.04852892,0.02907265,-0.032206908,-0.04450649,-0.02369661,0.00886328,0.0018687217,-0.04242907,0.010412385,-0.022661146,0.0251323,-0.07860962,-0.049228895,-0.034816697,0.0072931396,-0.076126836,0.0022941134,0.040625993,-0.022584403,-0.02668044,-0.083926745,0.00059464184,0.01081912,-0.0387231,0.0012095828,-0.009570069,-0.03989096,-0.0035962723,-0.0061948784,-0.008051233,-0.015285352,-0.055692874,0.049461327,0.045836356,-0.058764856,-0.03258089,-0.045178156,0.02232111,-7.792992E-05,-0.011558254,-0.014086625,0.019289404,-0.0275095,0.005532474,0.031212319,-0.0094762165,0.034799907,-0.008303266,-0.025290059,0.06045653,0.048618652,0.0005176311,0.014128672,0.0051756417,0.078393206,-0.04233729,-0.0